{"questionId":"9465","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>This question asks you to investigate regular <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"n\">\n  <mi>n</mi>\n</math></span>-sided polygons inscribed and circumscribed&nbsp;in a circle, and the perimeter of these as <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"n\">\n  <mi>n</mi>\n</math></span> tends to infinity, to make an approximation for <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"\\pi \">\n  <mi>π</mi>\n</math></span>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Let <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"{P_i}\\left( n \\right)\">\n  <mrow>\n    <msub>\n      <mi>P</mi>\n      <mi>i</mi>\n    </msub>\n  </mrow>\n  <mrow>\n    <mo>(</mo>\n    <mi>n</mi>\n    <mo>)</mo>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span> represent the perimeter of any <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"n\">\n  <mi>n</mi>\n</math></span>-sided regular polygon inscribed in a circle of&nbsp;radius 1 unit.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Consider an equilateral triangle ABC of side length, <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"x\">\n  <mi>x</mi>\n</math></span> units, circumscribed about a circle of&nbsp;radius 1 unit and centre O as shown in the following diagram.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/300c0ddb02b59d7560ae1722763f5b7c11cabf5a.png\"></p>\n<p>Let <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"{P_c}\\left( n \\right)\">\n  <mrow>\n    <msub>\n      <mi>P</mi>\n      <mi>c</mi>\n    </msub>\n  </mrow>\n  <mrow>\n    <mo>(</mo>\n    <mi>n</mi>\n    <mo>)</mo>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span> represent the perimeter of any <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"n\">\n  <mi>n</mi>\n</math></span>-sided regular polygon circumscribed about a&nbsp;circle of radius 1 unit.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>By writing&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"{P_c}\\left( n \\right)\"> <mrow> <msub> <mi>P</mi> <mi>c</mi> </msub> </mrow> <mrow> <mo>(</mo> <mi>n</mi> <mo>)</mo> </mrow> </math></span>&nbsp;in the form&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"\\frac{{2\\,{\\text{tan}}\\left( {\\frac{\\pi }{n}} \\right)}}{{\\frac{1}{n}}}\"> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>2</mn> <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace> <mrow> <mtext>tan</mtext> </mrow> <mrow> <mo>(</mo> <mrow> <mfrac> <mi>π</mi> <mi>n</mi> </mfrac> </mrow> <mo>)</mo> </mrow> </mrow> <mrow> <mfrac> <mn>1</mn> <mi>n</mi> </mfrac> </mrow> </mfrac> </math></span>, find&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"\\mathop {{\\text{lim}}}\\limits_{n \\to \\infty } {P_c}\\left( n \\right)\"> <munder> <mrow> <mrow> <mtext>lim</mtext> </mrow> </mrow> <mrow> <mi>n</mi> <mo stretchy=\"false\">→</mo> <mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi> </mrow> </munder> <mo>⁡</mo> <mrow> <msub> <mi>P</mi> <mi>c</mi> </msub> </mrow> <mrow> <mo>(</mo> <mi>n</mi> <mo>)</mo> </mrow> </math></span>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>consider&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"\\mathop {{\\text{lim}}}\\limits_{n \\to \\infty } 2n\\,{\\text{tan}}\\left( {\\frac{\\pi }{n}} \\right) = \\mathop {{\\text{lim}}}\\limits_{n \\to \\infty } \\left( {\\frac{{2\\,{\\text{tan}}\\left( {\\frac{\\pi }{n}} \\right)}}{{\\frac{1}{n}}}} \\right)\"> <munder> <mrow> <mrow> <mtext>lim</mtext> </mrow> </mrow> <mrow> <mi>n</mi> <mo stretchy=\"false\">→</mo> <mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi> </mrow> </munder> <mo>⁡</mo> <mn>2</mn> <mi>n</mi> <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace> <mrow> <mtext>tan</mtext> </mrow> <mrow> <mo>(</mo> <mrow> <mfrac> <mi>π</mi> <mi>n</mi> </mfrac> </mrow> <mo>)</mo> </mrow> <mo>=</mo> <munder> <mrow> <mrow> <mtext>lim</mtext> </mrow> </mrow> <mrow> <mi>n</mi> <mo stretchy=\"false\">→</mo> <mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi> </mrow> </munder> <mo>⁡</mo> <mrow> <mo>(</mo> <mrow> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>2</mn> <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace> <mrow> <mtext>tan</mtext> </mrow> <mrow> <mo>(</mo> <mrow> <mfrac> <mi>π</mi> <mi>n</mi> </mfrac> </mrow> <mo>)</mo> </mrow> </mrow> <mrow> <mfrac> <mn>1</mn> <mi>n</mi> </mfrac> </mrow> </mfrac> </mrow> <mo>)</mo> </mrow> </math></span></p>\n<p><span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\" = \\mathop {{\\text{lim}}}\\limits_{n \\to \\infty } \\left( {\\frac{{2\\,{\\text{tan}}\\left( {\\frac{\\pi }{n}} \\right)}}{{\\frac{1}{n}}}} \\right) = \\frac{0}{0}\"> <mo>=</mo> <munder> <mrow> <mrow> <mtext>lim</mtext> </mrow> </mrow> <mrow> <mi>n</mi> <mo stretchy=\"false\">→</mo> <mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi> </mrow> </munder> <mo>⁡</mo> <mrow> <mo>(</mo> <mrow> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>2</mn> <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace> <mrow> <mtext>tan</mtext> </mrow> <mrow> <mo>(</mo> <mrow> <mfrac> <mi>π</mi> <mi>n</mi> </mfrac> </mrow> <mo>)</mo> </mrow> </mrow> <mrow> <mfrac> <mn>1</mn> <mi>n</mi> </mfrac> </mrow> </mfrac> </mrow> <mo>)</mo> </mrow> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mn>0</mn> <mn>0</mn> </mfrac> </math></span>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>R1</strong></em></p>\n<p>attempt to use L’Hopital’s rule&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>M1</strong></em></p>\n<p><span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\" = \\mathop {{\\text{lim}}}\\limits_{n \\to \\infty } \\left( {\\frac{{ - \\frac{{2\\pi }}{{{n^2}}}{\\text{se}}{{\\text{c}}^2}\\left( {\\frac{\\pi }{n}} \\right)}}{{ - \\frac{1}{{{n^2}}}}}} \\right)\"> <mo>=</mo> <munder> <mrow> <mrow> <mtext>lim</mtext> </mrow> </mrow> <mrow> <mi>n</mi> <mo stretchy=\"false\">→</mo> <mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi> </mrow> </munder> <mo>⁡</mo> <mrow> <mo>(</mo> <mrow> <mfrac> <mrow> <mo>−</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>2</mn> <mi>π</mi> </mrow> <mrow> <mrow> <msup> <mi>n</mi> <mn>2</mn> </msup> </mrow> </mrow> </mfrac> <mrow> <mtext>se</mtext> </mrow> <mrow> <msup> <mrow> <mtext>c</mtext> </mrow> <mn>2</mn> </msup> </mrow> <mrow> <mo>(</mo> <mrow> <mfrac> <mi>π</mi> <mi>n</mi> </mfrac> </mrow> <mo>)</mo> </mrow> </mrow> <mrow> <mo>−</mo> <mfrac> <mn>1</mn> <mrow> <mrow> <msup> <mi>n</mi> <mn>2</mn> </msup> </mrow> </mrow> </mfrac> </mrow> </mfrac> </mrow> <mo>)</mo> </mrow> </math></span>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\" = 2\\pi \"> <mo>=</mo> <mn>2</mn> <mi>π</mi> </math></span>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><em><strong>[5 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"9465","referenceCode":"SPM.3.AHL.TZ0.1g","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"By writing P c ( n ) in the form 2 tan ( π n ) 1 n , find lim n → ∞ ⁡ P c ( n ) .","paper":"3","level":"HL","questionNumber":"g","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 5]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 5 —Calculus","Topic 5 —Calculus","AHL 5.13—Limits and L’Hopitals","Topic 5 —Calculus","AHL 5.19—Maclaurin series"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}